# File & Media Handling

Coding patterns for uploading, processing, storing, and serving files - images, documents, videos, or any user-generated content. IF your project handles file uploads or media, apply these patterns.

> All numeric values (thresholds, sizes, timings, percentages) in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Trust test (uploads)

**MUST** validate on server: size limits, allowlist, magic bytes - never trust client MIME/extension alone.

**Access test:** unauthorized download must fail - signed URL or auth-gated stream (`security.md`).

---

## Storage Strategy Decision

**Principle:** Storage and processing strategy should be determined by file size - small files can be handled differently than large ones.

[REFERENCE] Typical file size tiers and handling strategies:

Choose your storage approach based on file size and access patterns:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ File Size / Use Case        │ Storage Approach                      │
├─────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Tiny (< 100KB)              │ Base64 in DB field (inline)           │
│   e.g., small icons, logos  │   Pro: No extra infrastructure       │
│                             │   Con: Bloats DB, no CDN caching     │
├─────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Small (100KB - 2MB)         │ Base64 in DB OR object storage       │
│   e.g., icons, thumbnails   │   Choose based on read frequency     │
│                             │   and whether you need CDN/variants  │
├─────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Medium (2MB - 50MB)         │ Object storage (S3, R2, GCS)         │
│   e.g., documents, photos   │   Store URL/path in DB               │
│                             │   Serve via CDN for performance      │
├─────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Large (50MB+)               │ Object storage + chunked upload      │
│   e.g., videos, exports     │   Resumable uploads required         │
│                             │   Background processing pipeline     │
└─────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Base64 / Inline Storage Pattern (for small files)

```
When to use:
  - Files are small (< 2MB typically)
  - Few files per entity (1-3 images)
  - No need for CDN, variants, or separate processing
  - Simpler infrastructure is a priority

Flow (example - adapt to your client platform):
  Client: Convert file to base64 string (e.g. FileReader in browsers, native APIs on mobile)
  Client: Send base64 string in JSON body
  Server: Validate prefix (data:image/...) + estimate size from string length
  Server: Store as string field on the entity document
  Display: Use data URL directly as img src

Rules:
  - Mirror size limit on BOTH client and server
  - Validate MIME prefix on server (data:image/jpeg, data:image/png, etc.)
  - Estimate decoded size: Math.ceil(base64String.length * 3 / 4)
  - Be aware: large base64 strings in JWT/session tokens hurt performance
  - Consider: if images grow beyond 2-3 per entity, switch to object storage
```

### Object Storage Pattern (for medium/large files)

```
When to use:
  - Files are > 2MB or many files per entity
  - Need CDN delivery, variants (thumbnail/medium/large), or processing
  - Multi-region delivery matters
  - Need to serve files without loading from DB

Flow:
  Client: Upload via multipart form or presigned URL
  Server: Validate, process, store in bucket
  Server: Save file metadata (URL, size, type) in DB
  Display: Serve from CDN URL
```

