## Storage

### Where to Store Files

Refer to the **Storage Strategy Decision** table above to pick the right approach.

```
IN THE DATABASE (base64 string or small BLOB):
  - Valid for: small files < 2MB per entity (small images, icons, signatures)
  - Store as string field on the entity (e.g., entity.inlineImage)
  - Simpler architecture - no separate storage service needed
  - Trade-off: increases document/row size, no CDN, no variants

OBJECT STORAGE (S3, R2, GCS, MinIO):
  - Required for: files > 2MB, many files per entity, CDN delivery, variant generation
  - Store URL/path in DB, serve from CDN
  - Scales independently of the database

NEVER:
  - In the git repository
  - In the application's file system for production (doesn't scale, lost on deploy)
  - Large files (> 2MB) as base64 in session tokens or JWTs

For development:
  - Local file system is OK for dev/testing
  - Use the same API interface as production (so switching needs no code change)
```

### Storage Structure

```
{bucket}/
├── images/
│   ├── {uuid}-thumbnail.webp
│   ├── {uuid}-medium.webp
│   └── {uuid}-large.webp
├── files/
│   ├── {uuid}.pdf
│   └── {uuid}-preview.jpg
├── misc/
│   └── {uuid}.{ext}
└── temp/
    └── {uuid}.{ext}        <- cleaned up after 24 hours
```

### Database Record

**For inline/base64 storage** - the file IS the field:

```
{
  id: "entity-123",
  name: "...",
  inlineImage: "data:image/png;base64,iVBOR...",  // stored directly on the entity
  // No separate file record needed
}
```

**For object storage** - every file gets a separate record:

```
{
  id: "file-uuid",
  originalName: "quarterly-report.pdf",
  storagePath: "files/a1b2c3d4.pdf",
  mimeType: "application/pdf",
  size: 2456789,                          // bytes
  variants: {                             // for images
    thumbnail: "images/a1b2c3d4-thumbnail.webp",
    medium: "images/a1b2c3d4-medium.webp",
    large: "images/a1b2c3d4-large.webp"
  },
  uploadedBy: "user-123",
  entityType: "Resource",                  // what this file is attached to
  entityId: "resource-456",
  createdAt: "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z"
}
```

